Steps to do to run benchmark on blackwell:

To capture p99 inference latency on NVIDIA Blackwell, the fastest path is to rent time on a cloud that already offers Blackwell (B200 / GB200 / GB300), run a controlled load test, and export latency percentiles.

Where you can get Blackwell GPUs right now (practical options)

AWS EC2 P6-B200 (8× Blackwell B200 GPUs per instance)

Google Cloud Compute Engine A4 (A4 machine series uses NVIDIA B200 Blackwell GPUs)

CoreWeave (HGX B200 instances generally available; also Blackwell offerings)

Azure (Blackwell-based VM lines are emerging; e.g., Blackwell Ultra GB300 series info is published)

If you want the least friction for inference benchmarking, CoreWeave / AWS / GCP are typically the quickest routes because you can spin up the instance and run your harness immediately.

How to capture p99 latency correctly (minimal but solid methodology)

Pick your serving stack: vLLM, TensorRT-LLM, Triton, or your in-house server. (Use the same stack when comparing to H100.)

Warm-up: run a few hundred requests before measuring.

Fixed workload definition (important for p99):

model + quantization (FP16/BF16/FP8/FP4 if applicable)

prompt length + output length distribution

concurrency or request arrival rate (RPS)

Run at steady state for long enough to get stable tails (e.g., 10k–100k requests depending on variance).

Record per-request latency end-to-end and compute:

p50, p95, p99

also TTFT (time-to-first-token) and TPOT (time-per-output-token) if it’s an LLM

A simple, reliable benchmark pattern (what I recommend)

Generate load with locust or wrk2-style constant-rate generator (for HTTP), or a custom async client.

Emit latency histograms (Prometheus/OpenTelemetry) so p99 is computed consistently.

On the node, also capture GPU telemetry (utilization, memory, SM occupancy) so you can explain p99 spikes (queueing vs kernel vs KV/memory pressure).
